      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Justification for constitutive model selection (bilinear isotropic hardening for Ti-6Al-4V) with supporting material characterization data. Gradation 3 requires physics-based justification and literature support.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening selected for Ti-6Al-4V rod and screw bodies based on published tensile coupon data (ASTM E8) and prior FDA validation studies. Geometric nonlinearity enabled to capture large-displacement bending response. Model form consistent with established practice for metallic implant FEA at this deformation regime."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric dimensions sourced from measured specimen data; uncertainty ranges defined from population statistics. Gradation 3 requires measured input distributions, not nominal values alone.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus, yield strength, and tangent modulus derived from tensile coupon tests on production-lot material (n=10 coupons per lot). Geometric dimensions measured from each of the 11 test constructs via CMM. Input uncertainty ranges (±1 standard deviation) propagated through the model ensemble. A screening sensitivity study was performed to qualitatively rank input contributors; results are summarized in the UQ report narrative, confirming that yield strength and rod diameter variability are principal drivers of QoI spread."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
